@node not21 "FIRST PUBLIC RELEASE OF MIAMI DELUXE"
                      FIRST PUBLIC RELEASE OF MIAMI DELUXE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Nordic Global Inc. Ukiah, April 12th, 2000


For immediate press release

We are happy to announce the first public release, version 1.0c, of "Miami
Deluxe", our new high-end TCP/IP router stack for Internet and LAN access
(short: "MiamiDx").

MiamiDx is the successor of our successful "Miami" software, the most widely
installed TCP/IP Internet software for AmigaOS, and winner of the "Amiga
Achievement Award International" in 1998 for its functionality and ease of use.

Compared to Miami, MiamiDx provides the following additional features:

   - Support for multiple interfaces, e.g. Ethernet and PPP at the same time.

   - Routing between interfaces.

   - IP/NAT (IP masquerading), allowing fully transparent "modem sharing",
     similar to "WinGate", "SyGate", "WinRoute", "ipchains" etc. on other
     platforms. Eliminates the need to configure proxy servers.

   - Built-in SOCKS daemon, for even better compatibility of "modem sharing".

   - Built-in firewall. Fully auto-configuring, and thus extremely easy to set
     up. Combined with its very secure, state-of-the-art TCP/IP kernel the
     firewall provides Amiga users with extensive protection from Internet
     break-ins on all machines in the LAN.

   - Dial-on-demand. MiamiDx can automatically dial up your Internet connection
     if you try to access a web page from your web browser.

   - Interface control panel. An optional configurable window with status and
     statistics information for each interface, and buttons to go online and
     offline. This window takes up much less space than the full user
     interface.

   - Support for Unix domain sockets (AF_LOCAL/UNIX).

   - PPP improvements: PPP layer data encryption (40 or 128 bits) and data
     compression compatible with Windows-NT. Support for MS-CHAPv2. This makes
     MiamiDx compliant with the highest security standards configurable in
     Windows-NT servers.

   - Client driver for PPPoE, making MiamiDx the only AmigaOS software to
     support the new industry standard for DSL modems, used e.g. by T-DSL
     (DTAG, Germany), Sympatico (Canada) and Earthlink (USA).

   - Client drivers for PPTP and L2TP. This allows MiamiDx to connect to VPNs
     (Virtual Private Networks) using either Unix or Windows standard
     protocols.

   - Set of DNS tools from the BIND V8 distribution, including Addr, DiG,
     DNSQuery, Host and NSLookup.

   - MiamiFtp: Full-featured command line-based FTP client, with very high
     performance (async file I/O), support for CERN-style proxies (http://,
     ftp://), ftp proxying, resuming transfer ("reget") and many other
     features.

   - MiamiTelnet: telnet client, providing by far the most comprehensive set of
     features of any AmigaOS telnet client, including monochrome and color
     mode, VT100 emulation, SSH, SSL, SRP, rlogin, telnet, line mode, 8-bit
     support, XPR support, chat line, TN3270 and much more.

   - MiamiTelnetD: telnet/rlogin daemon for AmigaOS, the only one that emulates
     an AmigaOS console, making it compatible with most pagers and
     console-based editors.

MiamiDx 1.0c is available for download from www.nordicglobal.com. A demo version
(with a time limit and other limitations) is available for free. The full
registration costs US$ 60.00. An upgrade from a registered version of Miami (any
version) costs US$ 30.00.

The easiest way to register or upgrade is directly from your Amiga, after
installing MiamiDx, using our one-step "QuickRegistration" scheme, paying by
credit card. Registrations are also available from our web site and by email.

Holger Kruse
